This paddle loses grit very fast because it uses a spray on grit. Be aware that you will see a noticeable decrease in spin performance after it wears off.

After using this paddle for about a month, it did see a big drop off in spin. It started averaging about 1200 RPM. Personally, the drop didn't seem to affect my play much, but going from 1500 to 1200 is a pretty big drop. I dont think this is unique to the Hyperion. It's starting to appear that most paddles with this surface do degrade over time. Something else that may have lead to this is that my Hyperion had a loose edge guard that I had to glue. Mine feels noticeably softer than a brand new one. So perhaps my edge guard is playing a big role in this.
Unless mine was a dude, I do not recommend this paddle to anyone. Noticeably worse than the regular Hyperion. It’s closer to a Vision.

Tested the red and blue side of the FlipShot. Results are very similar. Be careful, this paddle is using grit like the Franklin Signature and Diadem Warrior. Which just means, it wears out very fast and will cause a noticeable drop in performance later.
The handle is listed as 5.7 inches but the way the handle is designed and the way you hold it, really doesn’t feel like a 5.7 inch handle. Maybe 5.3 inches or so.

This paddle is basically identical to the Diadem Warrior. All of the specs are the same except instead of nomex in the core, it’s kevlar. It does play slightly more powerful than the Warrior though. I would say this paddle is if like Diadem created a control and power version of the Warrior. The Pro Drive being the power verison.
I can't say for certain yet, but this feels very similar to the spray on Franklin grit. So I expect this to fade noticeably over time.
